        <div type="typology">
          <p>East (Mashriq) › Arabia › Oman</p>
          <p>Coastal dialect characterized by a juxtaposition of both Bedouin
              and sedentary type features</p>
        </div>

        <div type="general">
          <p>Al-Khaburah is one of the main settlements on the Bāṭinah coast
              of north-eastern Oman. There are significant differences between
              the speech of the people living at the coast proper and the
              inlanders who immigrated in great numbers to the coast bringing
              their dialectal peculiarities with them.</p>
        </div>

        <div type="researchHistory">
          <p>Hitherto the only description of the dialect of the town and its
              surroundings is <rs type="bibl" ref="zotID:G5BL9R3B">Brockett
                1985</rs>. This book is based on fieldwork carried out in the
              late 1970s/early 1980s. It offers a short introduction into
              phonology and morphology and discusses some special syntactical
              features. The main part is dedicated to lexicography with a focus
              on agricultural terms. No texts have been published in Khaburah
              Arabic nor are there any sound files available.</p>
        </div>
